{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 01:41:22.883790", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary of overall health\\n- Most of the OSPF domain is healthy: core routers and the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) exchange routes successfully, and a host in the 10.2.1.0/24 site (host_2_1_1_1) can resolve DNS and reach HTTP services (both web frontends and the load balancer).\\n- A specific distribution segment (10.1.1.0/24) is isolated from the rest of the network. Its distribution router (router_dist_1_1) is not forming an OSPF adjacency to the core, so it does not learn or advertise routes beyond its directly connected networks.\\n\\nDetected anomalies\\n1) Loss of routing for subnet 10.1.1.0/24 across OSPF\\n- router_core_1 does not have any route to 10.1.1.0/24 (% Network not in table on query).\\n- server_access_router has OSPF routes to 10.1.2.0/24, 10.1.3.0/24, 10.1.4.0/24, but 10.1.1.0/24 is missing.\\n- router_dist_1_1’s OSPF shows zero neighbors and its routing table contains only connected routes (10.1.1.0/24 and 172.16.0.6/31); there are no learned routes to the server farm 10.200.0.0/24.\\n\\n2) Host reachability consistent with the above isolation\\n- host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.17/24, GW 10.1.1.1) fails to ping DNS (10.200.0.2) and the load balancer (10.200.0.7) with “Network is unreachable,” consistent with upstream routing being unavailable from router_dist_1_1.\\n- In contrast, host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.22/24) can ping DNS and the load balancer and retrieves web content normally, indicating the rest of the OSPF domain and server farm are fine.\\n\\nFault localization\\n- The failure is localized to the OSPF adjacency on the link between router_core_1 and router_dist_1_1:\\n  - Link: 172.16.0.6/31 (router_core_1 eth2 = 172.16.0.6) <-> 172.16.0.7/31 (router_dist_1_1 eth0 = 172.16.0.7).\\n  - IP connectivity on the link works (ICMP between 172.16.0.6 and 172.16.0.7 succeeds).\\n  - OSPF adjacency does not form on either side:\\n    - router_core_1: OSPF on eth2 (172.16.0.6/31, area 0.0.0.1) shows “Neighbor Count 0, State DR.”\\n    - router_dist_1_1: OSPF on eth0 (172.16.0.7/31, area 0.0.0.1) shows “Neighbor Count 0, State DR.”\\n    - “show ip ospf neighbor” on router_dist_1_1 returns no neighbors.\\n- Because router_dist_1_1 is not adjacent to the core, it does not advertise 10.1.1.0/24 into OSPF and does not learn routes (e.g., 10.200.0.0/24) needed for hosts to reach the server farm.\\n\\nRoot cause assessment\\n- The immediate root cause is an OSPF control-plane failure on the 172.16.0.6/31 link between router_core_1 and router_dist_1_1: both sides are up at L3 but are not exchanging OSPF Hellos/adjacency.\\n- Configuration on both sides shows the interface addresses and area assignment appear correct (both include network 172.16.0.6/31 area 1). Hello/dead timers and no-auth settings match, and iptables on router_dist_1_1 is permissive.\\n- Symptom pattern suggests OSPF packets are not being exchanged/recognized on that specific interface pair despite IP ping working; this is consistent with an OSPF interface-level issue (e.g., network type/behavior on a /31 link not forming adjacency on router_dist_1_1) rather than a general connectivity or filtering issue.\\n- Consequence: 10.1.1.0/24 is not present in the OSPF domain. Hosts in that subnet cannot reach DNS (10.200.0.2), the load balancer (10.200.0.7), or other server subnets via their default gateway 10.1.1.1.\\n\\nSupporting evidence (key extracts)\\n- host_1_1_1_1:\\n  - IP config: 10.1.1.17/24, default via 10.1.1.1; resolv.conf nameserver 10.200.0.2.\\n  - Pings to dns_server and load_balancer: “Network is unreachable.”\\n- host_2_1_1_1:\\n  - Successfully pings DNS and load balancer; HTTP curls to web frontends succeed with normal latency.\\n- router_core_1:\\n  - “show ip route 10.1.1.0/24” => not in table.\\n  - OSPF interface eth2 172.16.0.6/31 (area 0.0.0.1): State DR, Neighbor Count 0.\\n- router_dist_1_1:\\n  - OSPF neighbors: none.\\n  - “show ip ospf interface” shows eth0 (172.16.0.7/31 area 0.0.0.1) DR with no neighbors.\\n  - Route table only has connected routes; no route to 10.200.0.0/24.\\n- server_access_router:\\n  - OSPF adjacency up with core (via 172.16.0.22/31). Routes to 10.1.2.0/24–10.1.4.0/24 present; 10.1.1.0/24 missing.\\n  - 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- An anomaly exists: the OSPF adjacency between router_core_1 and router_dist_1_1 on 172.16.0.6/31 is down. This prevents 10.1.1.0/24 from participating in the OSPF domain, isolating hosts in that subnet from DNS and server farm services. The fault is localized to OSPF on the router_dist_1_1 <-> router_core_1 link (likely an OSPF interface-level misbehavior on router_dist_1_1), rather than a general transport/connectivity issue., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='537b7b65-a3f1-488d-b772-485d30ce43ed'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
